________________________<br>
<br>
In Shards of Rimni, Dylan Hunt and Harper undergo a &quot;buddy&quot; mission of sorts to outsmart a bunch of goons who are seeking the shards of Rimni. Putting all the shards together creates some sort of ultimate artifact, like the Engine of Creation from last season.<br>
<br>
A problem with the episode is that the villains are incredibly stupid. They line themselves up, and Dylan knocks them down, there's no intrigue, no tension, no drama. It's boring.<br>
<br>
Dylan Hunt is unquestionably the hero of this series. He isn't an anti-hero, he isn't a bit player in an all-important emsemble. He's the lead, the hero of the show. With that as a given, why do his adversaries have to be written as such dunces?<br>
<br>
I would point to the classic confrontation of Kirk vs Khan, whether in Space Seed or The Wrath of Khan. Khan made mistakes, Kirk capitalized on them. A little luck helped as well. But there was no mistaking that Khan was a very intelligent adversary, and Kirk was fighting for his life in battling him. After each of their confrontations, could you say Kirk was the smarter man? No, he had to earn every win against Khan, an adversary who would never give away victory lightly.<br>
<br>
I mention this because if Kirk simply shows up and says &quot;I'm the hero, dumb bad guys line up for me&quot;, he isn't being heroic about anything. Kirk is a hero because his adversary was Khan. Were Zeus or Abelard from this Andromeda episode to have been his adversary, would anyone consider Kirk a resourceful hero? No, but they do because of the mettle of his opponent, Khan.<br>
<br>
And I'm not simply speaking of petty adversaries like Zeus and Abelard. What of the cosmic adversaries like the Magog god &quot;Sparky&quot;? What of the Tunnel aliens? In scene after scene after scene, we got to know Khan, what drove him, what his ambitions were. And finally, what the focus of his vengeance was. <br>
<br>
Have we heard anything of the ambitions of Sparky? Do we know what drives him? Does he have any personality at all that makes him a compelling figure? No to all questions. He just stands there and glows, doing nothing. Goodness, just one scene of him threatening Dylan would tell us something of his motivation, instead he disappears as meaninglessly as he arrived.<br>
<br>
Reading back on episode synopsis last season, I see they were attempting to build a story arc where the &quot;Tunnelers&quot; have an issue with Dylan, the Andromeda, or the new Commonwealth. That was the intent, do we ever see it given voice? No, they are left as mysterious and irrelevant now as they were when they were introduced. If you don't give them a personality, who cares why they are there? <br>
<br>
Even when the Borg on Star Trek were just a amorphous threat without a central figure, we had the dire descriptions of Guinan to make them interesting. Yet we have no one to fill us in on either Sparky or the Tunnelers, they exist as disembodied CGI effects without content or interest.<br>
<br>
Kirk vs Khan. A classic confrontation, and it took two to tango. Please, someone keep this in mind when penning Dylan Hunt as the &quot;hero&quot; in the future. The villains he has fought have the planning ability of Forrest Gump or Rainman. When Dylan beats these dunces, it reflects just as badly on him.<br>
<br>
-Ogami <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003B75><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bslipstreambbs12353.showUserPublicProfile?gid=heroicfool>HeroicFool</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://avatarshere.topcities.com/p/explosionwer.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#0000FF, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='user title'>Triumvir</span></td></tr></table>
